In regard to the last count, itis interesting to learn that this serious charge of fartum¹ has no reference to the Greek originale employed, but only to earlier Latin poete. Pro- fessional etiquette demanded that when a writer had turned a Greek play into Latin, that play should be considered his peerdiar property. To this charge Terence pleads ‘not guilty,’ either claiming that he was ignorant of any pre- vious use of the play, or proving that his own was entirely new.
